# C. S. Lewis on the Reading of Old Books

There is a strange idea abroad that in every subject the ancient books should be
read only by the professional, and that the amateur should content himself with
the modern books.[^intro] Lewis thought this exactly backwards.

:::callout{type=note}
This essay first appeared in 1944 as the introduction to a translation of
Athanasius. The argument it makes about *books* turns out to be an argument
about *formats* too: what survives is what stays readable.
:::

## The argument in his own words

> Naturally, since I myself am a writer, I do not wish the ordinary reader to
> read no modern books. But if he must read only the new or only the old, I
> would advise him to read the old.
>
> > And I would give him this advice precisely because he is an amateur and
> > therefore much less protected than the expert against the dangers of an
> > exclusive contemporary diet.

The quotation above nests one block inside another, two levels deep, and the
format keeps both rules intact.

## Three works, three doors

Readers arrive at Lewis through very different books. Pick a door:

::::tabs
:::tab{title=Apologetics}
*Mere Christianity* began as wartime radio talks. Its method is plain: start
from something the listener already grants, then walk one careful step at a time.
:::
:::tab{title=Fiction}
*The Chronicles of Narnia* smuggle the same ideas past what he called the
"watchful dragons" of a too-solemn reverence.
:::
:::tab{title=Grief}
*A Grief Observed*, published under a pseudonym, is the unguarded notebook of a
man watching his own faith tested by loss.
:::
::::

## A line worth typesetting

He believed glory was not vanity but *weight*, a thing with real mass. If we let
ourselves be playful and write that as an equation, the point is that the term
never vanishes:

```math
\lim_{t \to \infty} \text{Glory}(t) \neq 0
```

## The shape of a life

```diagram
timeline
  title A brief life of C. S. Lewis
  1898 : Born in Belfast
  1917 : Trenches of the First World War
  1931 : Returns to Christian faith
  1942 : The Screwtape Letters
  1950 : The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe
  1963 : Dies in Oxford
```

## For the curious

alt-accordion below hides the full closing paragraph until you want it.

:::accordion{title="Read the famous closing lines"}
He wrote that there are no *ordinary* people, that you have never talked to a
mere mortal. Nations, cultures, arts, civilisations, these are mortal, and their
life is to ours as the life of a gnat. But it is immortals whom we joke with,
work with, marry, snub, and exploit.
:::

The passage above is full of the punctuation that breaks lesser parsers:
apostrophes, commas in series, and emphasis pressed right up against words. It
round-trips cleanly.

[^intro]: From *On the Reading of Old Books*, C. S. Lewis, 1944. The essay is now
in the public domain in several jurisdictions and is widely anthologised.
